The common good of society depends upon the search for truth and its free exposition. Academic Freedom is essential to these purposes:
Members are entitled to the freedom to carry out research and to publish the results, to the freedom to teach and discuss their subjects, and to the freedom from institutional censorship;
Academic Freedom carries with it the duty to use that freedom in a responsible way;
Academic Freedom does not confer legal immunity; nor does it diminish one's obligation to meet one's responsibilities under this Collective Agreement.

"Medical Certificate" means a certificate signed by a qualified health-care professional and submitted to the Wellness Department verifying:
that a medical condition exists;
if a treatment plan has been recommended, whether the Member is participating, to the best of the qualified health-care professional's knowledge;
the anticipated date upon which the Member is expected to be able to meet the full or modified responsibilities of his/her position; and
any medical limitations or restrictions that impact the Member's ability to meet the full or modified responsibilities of his/her position; or
for the purposes of Compassionate Care Leave in Article 33.08.3, that a Family Member has a serious medical condition with a significant risk of death within twenty-six (26) weeks from the date the certificate is issued, or if the leave began prior to the certificate from the date the leave commenced, and that the Family Member requires the care or support of one or more Family Members.

“Procedural fairness” shall mean any and all of the following:
the duty of an adjudicator to make a decision without a reasonable apprehension of bias or a conflict of interest (prior familiarity with the facts of a case does not, by itself, constitute a reasonable apprehension of bias, nor do past friendly or unfriendly relationships);
the duty of an adjudicator to interpret and apply the Collective Agreement, including criteria of Articles 12, 14, and 15.06 in a reasonable and equitable manner (a disagreement with a decision or judgement does not, in itself, constitute a misinterpretation or misapplication of the Collective Agreement, nor does it constitute an unreasonable interpretation or application of the Collective Agreement, nor does differential treatment, in itself, constitute evidence of inequitable treatment between members when appropriate rationale can be provided);
the duty of an adjudicator to ensure that adequate evidence is presented or collected to meet the standard of proof appropriate to support the decision and that such evidence is duly and appropriately considered;
the duty of an adjudicator to inform Members of their right to advice and representation from their Association and to allow such advice and representation without hindrance;
that the parties to a procedure have a right to know all evidence presented and used in the decision making process;
that the parties to a procedure have an opportunity to respond to all evidence presented and used in the decision making process;
that the parties to the procedure have a reasonable opportunity to present their case to adjudicator or adjudicators; and
that principles of natural justice are applied.

In the event of a strike or lockout involving members of other bargaining units at the University, Members of the Academic Staff:
shall not be required to perform the work of the members of those other bargaining units during the job action by those other members;
shall not be subject to new or additional duties, requirements, or work rules as a result of the strike or lockout beyond those required by law for the preservation of life, personal safety or health of the public or the maintenance and administration of law and order.

Inactive Members are those employees of the Board who:
are Senior Academic Administrators (as specified in Article 2), for the term(s) of their appointments as Senior Academic Administrators, and for any period(s) of administrative leave;
are Members appointed through Order in Council to serve on the Board, for the duration of their appointments to the Board.

The Board recognizes the utility of providing office space to the Association and agrees to continue to provide the current resources or equivalent in accordance with past practice:
the use of suitable office space and accommodations;
access to telecommunications and internet resources at internal rate, paid by the Association;
access to internal services such as mail delivery and meeting rooms on campus(es);
access to the University's facilities such as parking and identification cards for the Association's staff at prevailing internal rates;
one (1) Lot E parking permit, plus one (1) departmental rover parking permit at the prevailing internal rates, paid by the Association.

At no cost to the Association, the Association shall be entitled to the equivalent time in three-(3)-credit hour courses (the single course release) on the following basis:
five (5) single course releases in any Year;
two (2) additional single course releases in any Bargaining Year.

The Association is permitted to buy single course releases over and above the course releases under Article 5.05.2 on the following basis:
up to eight (8) single course releases in any Year;
two (2) additional single course releases in any Bargaining Year;
the Association shall remit to the Board an amount equal to the minimum Sessional Lecturer stipend plus 25%, as identified in Schedule A of this Collective Agreement for each course release so purchased under Article 5.05.3;
should the Association request that course releases be accorded to a Member at a rate of two (2) or more course releases in one (1) Academic Year, all releases in that Academic Year shall be permitted through the Association remitting to the Board a total amount equal to one third (1/3) of the minimum salary for an Associate Professor plus 25%, such minimum as identified in Schedule A.01.1 of this Collective Agreement.

