A program may be declared redundant for one or more of the following reasons:
changing Board priorities or restructuring of the University’s academic programs: as a consequence of a decision by the Board, after receiving recommendations from GFC;
low student enrolment: when recent history and reasonable projections into the future indicate that the level of enrolment, in proportion to the resources committed to that program, will continue for more than three (3) years significantly below the average of the relevant faculty;
a material loss of funding given to the Board for the support of the specific program;
other external factors which specifically affect enrolment in the particular program and over which the Board has no control, such as changes in the requirements for certification in various professions.

The Redundancy Committee shall be composed as follows:
a chair appointed by GFC;
two (2) other members and one (1) alternate appointed by the GFC;
one (1) member appointed by the Vice-President (Academic);
the Dean of the Faculty involved; and,
one (1) member, with voice but not vote, appointed by the Association.

The Redundancy Committee shall establish its own procedures, except that:
its hearings shall be open to the University community;
its quorum shall be all of its voting members;
reasonable effort shall be made to schedule meetings to allow attendance by the non-voting member.

Concurrent with any offer under Articles 13.02.8 or 25.03.6(a), the Board shall make reasonable efforts to offer to each probationary, continuing, or tenured Member in a redundant program one or more of the following, as deemed appropriate by the Board:
reassignment according to Article 25.03.7;
any other alternative which may be implemented with the mutual consent of the Board and the Member.

To qualify for Maternity and/or Parental Leave under Article 33.03, the Member must meet the following criteria:
to apply for Maternity Leave the Member must be pregnant;
the Member must provide documentation of their EI benefits eligibility;
the Member holds a probationary appointment, a tenured appointment/continuing appointment, or is in the second or subsequent year of a multi-year term appointment, or is in the second or subsequent year of consecutive term appointments;
if the University maintains an approved SUB Plan, the Member must comply with the regulations established by that Plan;
the Member applies to the Dean as soon as possible in advance of the date of the proposed leave so that the Dean may make adequate arrangements for the performance of the Member’s assigned duties;
the Member submits to the Wellness Department either a Medical Certificate which specifies the expected date of delivery, or documentation regarding the anticipated date of placement for an adopted child(ren);
the proposed period of leave includes the expected date of delivery or of placement, unless otherwise mutually agreed between the Dean and the Member.

When one or more of the following conditions exist, the Dean may recommend the appointment of a Sessional Lecturer:
to replace a Member who is on leave or on another assignment of duties;
when the search for an individual with the required qualifications for an advertised continuing position is unsuccessful;
when the appointment is for a pilot project of limited duration;
when unanticipated enrolment increases makes such an appointment necessary in the short term;
to integrate members of a professional or other community into the University's teaching program; or
when a person with the required qualifications fills a limited ongoing pedagogical need of a Department/Area or Faculty/Library curriculum.

The duties of a Sessional Lecturer will be clearly identified by the Dean in a letter of appointment. The letter will:
make reference to this Collective Agreement with its URL;
identify the starting and termination dates of the contract;
identify the rank and salary of the appointment;
identify the course(s) to be taught and any special requirements;
specify a start date consistent with the Member acquiring Library privileges, computer network access, a University e-mail account and any other relevant services, in advance of the commencement of the semester or session;
provide information on compensation should the course be cancelled (see Schedule );
if the offer is made less than forty-five (45) days before the start of the semester, information on the compensation outlined in Schedule A; and
contain any other relevant information.

A Sessional Lecturer shall be appointed at the rank of Sessional Lecturer II if he/she has not received a performance evaluation that is less than satisfactory within the past three (3) years, and any one of the following applies:
the individual has taught at least five (5) courses at the University within the past three (3) years;
the individual was previously appointed at the rank of Sessional Lecturer II;
the individual has held an appointment as a Faculty Member, Professional Librarian, Instructor or Academic Assistant; or
the individual teaches more than one course in a semester, as in Article 34.01.5.

