I have read and agree to abide by the provisions of the Faculty Handbook that bear on Conflict of Interest and/or Commitment, including but not limited to the following:
Article 11.03.1(i), which deals specifically with current or anticipated conflicts of interest with respect to evaluative and supervisory relationships between Members and students;
Article 11.03.2(b)(iii) and 11.03.2(b)(iv), which deal specifically with current or anticipated conflicts of interest with respect to Member's responsibilities as scholars;
Article 11.04, which defines the terms Conflict of Interest and/or Commitment and provides a process for a Member to report any current or anticipated conflicts and a means to evaluate and resolve any such conflicts in consultation with the Member's Dean;
Articles 11.03.2(b)(iii), 11.03.2(b)(iv), 13.10.1 through 13.10.5, and 13.11.2, which deal specifically with current or anticipated conflicts of commitment with respect to Member's external professional activities;
Article 17.09, which deals specifically with current or anticipated conflicts of interest or reasonable apprehension of bias with respect to Member's participation on personnel committees.

The Board and ULFA ("the Parties") agree to the following in resolution of two individual grievances and a policy grievance claimed by ULFA on August 15, 2017 regarding the Articles 31.05/31.06 merit pool/fund contributions on behalf of academic staff who are employed on less than full-time equivalent (FTE) contracts:
Merit pool/fund contributions are established in Faculty Handbook Articles 15 or 21, and are for each Member who is eligible to access the merit pool/fund, in Schedule A, Table A.01 (the "Per Member Contribution").
Beginning with the 2017/18 evaluation period, the Per Member Contribution shall be made at the full load merit pool/fund levels as specified in Schedule A, Table A.01, regardless of whether the Member is assigned to a less than 1.0 FTE status.
For the 2017/18 evaluation period, the Board agrees to make the following on-time only contributions:
A lump-sum contribution to the merit fund as defined in Article 15 and 31 for Instructors/Academic Assistants, in the amount of $11,000; and
A lump-sum contribution in the aggregate amount of $3,500 for all the Faculty/Library merit pools as defined in Article 21 and 31 for faculty members and professional librarians to be allocated amongst the Faculty/Library merit pools proportionally to the number of faculty members and professional librarians eligible to receive funds from each merit pool.
As of July 1, 2019, letters summarizing annual salaries as of July 1 each year shall be issued to each Member, containing the following:
June 30 salary;
cost of living adjustment amount and percentage (if any);
career progress increment amount (if any);
merit increment amount (if any); and
the resultant July 1 salary, as the sum of a. to d. in this clause.
As of July 1, 2019, the letters described in clause Q.01.4 above shall also include, for each faculty member and professional Librarian in an academic unit, a summary of:
how the academic unit's merit pool is calculated;
the number of merit units being awarded in that academic unit;
the monetary value of a merit unit in that academic unit;
the distribution of merit units within that academic unit.
As of July 1, 2019, the letters described in clause Q.01.4 above shall also include, for each Instructor/Academic Assistant, a summary of:
the number of Members for whom contributions are being made to the merit fund;
the total monetary value of the merit fund; and
the monetary value of a merit fund award for an Instructor/Academic Assistant with a performance rating score of 1.0.
All elements within this Memorandum of Understanding are agreed to by the Parties without prejudice to any other unresolved grievances between the Parties.

Accommodation is understood as any temporary or permanent measure used to remove a barrier which prevents an otherwise qualified Members from performing all or part of their normal duties to at least satisfactory performance standards. Accommodation may include, but is not limited to:
adjustments to physical workspace;
provision of tools or equipment;
modification of a Member’s duties, workload, or work practices; and/or
modification of work plans, annual assessments or timing of probationary/re-appointment/continuing appointment/tenure/promotion reviews.

The Parties hereby agree to complete the restructuring of the Collective Agreement as in the attached chart during the Parties’ next round of negotiations (beginning in 2020), with a section applying to all Members (except where explicitly noted to the contrary), a section applying to all Members except Sessional Lecturers (except where explicitly noted to the contrary), and individual Articles that apply to specific job categories. In particular (in what follows Article numbers refer to the numbering from the 2016-18 Faculty Handbook), the Parties agree that:
where possible, language shall be written and included in one location, so that it applies as broadly as possible;
there shall be a new Article (“XX”) into which the language relating to evaluation that currently appears in Articles 12, 13, 14, 15, and 21 shall be moved;
there shall be a new Article (“ZZ”) addressing STP procedures, based on the existing Article 20.03 but written so as to apply to all such procedures wherever possible;
material from Articles 14 and 15 shall be merged into Articles 13, 17, 18, 19, 20, and 21 so that these Articles apply to all Members other than Sessional Lecturers, or (in the case of Article 18) to all Members; and
Articles 21 and 32 shall be reorganised so that Article 21 includes all information relating to increments and how these are calculated, while Article 32 includes all other information relating to salary and benefits.
